    <p>
      Real-Time Health is our catch-phrase to point out that most of your health care documentation is not real time. It is on Doctor Time - By that I mean your health is measured when you go to the doctor. Which is fine for what they are trying to accomplish.
    </p>
    <p>
      However we are not trying to accomplish the same thing as what has been done, so we need to change how we measure health. The first step is to create a medical record for the rest of the time, the times when you are not at the doctor. This way we can see problems that are developing rather than waiting for the problem
      to burst onto the scene fully formed. This is the main goal of the Ajax Health Web app. It will be the way we track changes over time, decide who needs what measured and how often, figure out who has measurements coming up soon, and the various other logistical challenges that real time health tracking create.
    </p>
    <p>
      The medical record for the rest of the time will look very different from your standard medical record. We are going to be collecting measurements, both quantitative and qualitative, and tracking them over time. Quantitative measures include things like weight, potassium levels, protein in urine, and water as a percent of blood and so on.
      Qualitative measures are things like number of time gone to doctor in last 3 months, how does your knee feel, what happens to your energy level over the course of the day, et cetera. From these measures we will be able to assemble a picture of the health of various subsets of a population. We will be able to say that white men over the age of 50 gained 2lb on average this year.
      Black women between 25 and 50 had an increase in insulin in the blood stream. Tallahassee is going to the doctor less frequently.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is in stark contrast to a typical medical record. Traditional medical records list what the patient was like on the visit, and what happened to them. You can compare over time what the patient was like, but only for the medical records you have. If the patient is going between doctors, you must get medical records from each doctor, load them into a system, and analyze them over time.
      Even after you have done that, there is still the issue of the medical record only representing a very small fraction of your days. The medical record may well be very accurate and complete with regards to your visit to that provider on that day, but leaves out everything else.
    </p>
    <p>
      When compared to what a payer knows about a patient, Ajax Health again has many advantages. Payers have all the patient's demographic data and all their claims history. But claims do not paint a picture of health, they tell the payer what they owe for services rendered. The payers have the advantage of knowing more about a patient over time
      than any given provider since they get claims from all the providers a patient goes to. But that data is less rich in information.
    </p>
    <P>
      Another benefit of the measure and track method is that it limits the damage done by patient miss-representation. While I will not go so far to say that patients are liars, they will certainly leave things out. Ask an overweight patient about their eating habits and see what they say. Regardless of the answer, there is no way to know. Maybe they did only eat 2 crackers, or maybe ate two crackers with their 4 pounds of cheese.
      To the Ajax Health System it is irrelevant how much you ate, only that your weight went up or down. This is one of the keys of our approach - Patients are not always helpful and providers are concerned with the patients in their waiting room. Ajax Health does not care what you say, only what we measured and we measure more often than when you are at the doctors.
    </P>
    <p>
      Real-Time health is here to solve real time problems. Your health does not deteriorate or improve only when you are at a provider’s office - it is in constant flux. We are going to measure this flux and bring data to bear that has never been available before.
    </p>
