    <p>
      Wellness programs are the other way we bring value to the healthcare landscape. The Affordable Care Act (ACA) had many provisions, more than any one person knows about. One of the lesser known and implemented ones are an expansion of health contingent wellness programs.
    </p>
    <p>
    The reason that we have not seen more of these is simple, before the ACA, most health plans were in effect health contingent wellness plans. This is due to the practice known as medical underwriting. Under this system your insurance cost varies based on your medical conditions. If you have cancer, you also have a higher insurance premium.
    One of the biggest and well known aspects of the ACA is the prohibition against medical underwriting in the small group and individual markets. Large groups can still medically underwrite but since large groups have more people, it is less impactful since risk can be spread out amongst the larger group size. Now that medical underwriting is out, payers must use community rating in the small
    Group and individual markets. Community underwriting looks at the whole community and then sets rates. This way each individual makes less of an impact on the rate setting process since the community is much larger than a small group.
    </p>
    <p>
      The ACA increased the percentage of health premium that can be awarded to a wellness program participant from 20% to 30% of the member’s premium, with programs aimed at getting people to quit smoking going up to 50% of the premium. The statewide average health premium is $460 a month in Florida, which means that a wellness program participant is eligible for a 30% rebate could earn $1656 dollars a year!
      That is no small amount, and a family of 4 could reap several thousand dollars a year in wellness program benefits.
    </p>
    <p>
      The caveat to wellness programs is that they cannot be a back door into medical underwriting. That is to say you cannot give someone a payout for having not smoked if the never smoked, nor could you give a skinny person a payout if they did not lose weight during the period and were already skinny. They must make progress during the period, and then their premium goes back to the usual level next period.
      The thought is that if everyone in a plan is participating in the wellness program then their success as a group will lead to lower premiums for everyone. This is also the exact same goal as population health management.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since we are already going to have access to health information over time, adding in a wellness program component to our offerings is a natural fit. It allows us to offer patients motivation in the form of cash rewards and to expand our value to the payers. Payers do not have the
      systems in place to manage wellness programs, however they would love for their patients to be healthier. With the onset of community rating, the payers win with wellness programs since it allows them the ability to set rates high for everyone and then pay the people who are making a difference.
    </p>
    <p>
      So, this all sounds great, but what is your plan? Read on to find out more about our methodology.
    </p>
