    <p>
      Our solution to the problem of population health management is a new type of practice management system, Ajax Health. But what will this system do that other practice management systems don’t do, and why is that relevant?
    </p>
    <p>
      To explain that we need to take a step back. Healthcare in the US has a similar pattern across specialties and facilities - Doctors decide and nurses do. While that is an over simplification to the max (Surgeons both decide and do for example), it is a useful oversimplification in our case.
      Recall that Ajax Health is a facility, not a provider. We are making a place where providers can do a specific type of work - And that work is track health measures over time. Who decides what we track over time? Doctors. Once that decision is made, nurses and techs will do the heavy lifting of taking the measurements specified in a doctor's
      course of observation.
    </p>
    <p>
      A Course of Observation is a set of measurements and time frames for those measurements. It will be designed with a certain population in mind and have a specific objective. For example, if our objective is to reduce the number of pre-diabetic adult males in Tallahassee then we need to decide what measurement will categorize people as pre-diabetic or not.
      For type 2 diabetes, a doctor might decide that the important markers are weight compared to height (BMI) and insulin resistance. Those markers are to be measured quarterly since we are working with pre-diabetics at this point. Once this course has been decided upon, BMI and insulin resistance on a quarterly basis, it is assigned to a population.
    </p>
    <p>
      Once we have a population and a course of treatment, the facility springs into action. We are going to need to track all these people down, figure out how to measure them on a routine basis, and provide the results of these measurements to the providers who are interested. That is where the practice management system becomes crucial - it will keep track of who needs what measured when and what is the 
      best way to get their measures. Once the measures are captured, they are tracked over time and compared to the course of observation. People who achieve the goal of the course (in our example, lower the number of pre-diabetic adult males in Tallahassee) will be eligible for some sort of wellness program benefit.
    </p>
    <p>
      And that is how all the pieces fit together. Of course it is one thing to put up a poorly spelled web page that talks about how we are going to change the world with our new and nifty gadget. It is another thing entirely to actually do it...
    </p>
